An occultist, whose works I skimmed through a few days ago, mentioned that many of his "colleagues" liked "adjusting" their biography: They would interpret their past in a certain way to "fit" their current beliefs, then change them, after which their past also seemed to "change"

Reminded me of reading stories of transsexuals who mentioned they "felt that way" from before their realized they experienced dysphoria - same urges maybe would be interpreted as "weakness" if they adopted rightist/masculine ideology, "not belonging to this world" for monasticism

In a way, it just shows that the past is something alive, that does not exist separately, but "flows" from a person, so if you help someone, in terms of health, dignity, love, etc. so you will also change his past. Nothing is as static as it seems, memories are living entities.

And also it's good not to mythologize oneself as the maguses do and try to fit your past to a "narrative" that only mutilates its richness, but embrace and dignify its shameful (but not vulgar) aspects like vidya addictions, moments of uncertainty, of feeling lost in the world...
